The '''Janata Tower Case''' was a corruption [[criminal case|case]] in Bangladesh over Janata tower in Karwan Bazar in Dhaka. The case lead to the conviction of former military dictator H. M. Ershad.
== Background == Janata Tower is an eleven storey building located in [[Kawran Bazar|Karwan Bazar]], [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://archive.thedailystar.net/2005/01/30/d501302505104.htm|title = Janata Tower to get a facelift soon|website = archive.thedailystar.net|access-date = 2016-05-06}}</ref> It was originally planned to be 15 floors. After construction stopped in 1991 when General Ershad stepped down the tower became a home for squatters.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://archive.thedailystar.net/2005/12/07/d512072505107.htm|title = Janata Tower remains unutilised for long|last = Ayon|first = Kausar Islam|website = archive.thedailystar.net|access-date = 2016-05-06}}</ref>
== History == On 14 April 1991 the Bureau of Anti Corruption (today [[Anti Corruption Commission Bangladesh|Anti Corruption Commission]]) filed a case against 17 people including former president and military autocrat [[Hussain Muhammad Ershad|Hussein Mohammad Ershad]] and 19 others with Tejgaon Police Station.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url = http://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2008/11/12/sc-upholds-hc-rule-in-janata-tower-case|title = SC upholds HC rule in Janata Tower case|website = bdnews24.com|access-date = 2016-05-06}}</ref> He was charged with abuse of power for collusion with [[M. M. Rahmat Ullah]] in allotting the land for the project; and possessing unaccounted money. The [[Chief Justice of Bangladesh|Justice]] in his 91 -page verdict said General Ershad was found guilty under the Prevention Act; on November 20, 2000, the justice sentenced the former president to seven years' imprisonment.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GZ8UAQAAIAAJ|title=Asian News Digest: A Weekly Record on Governance, Economy, Development, Human Rights, and Environment|date=2001-01-01|publisher=Asian News Chroniclers|page=1090|language=en}}</ref> The building was acquired by Bangladesh government.<ref name=":0" /> As a result, Ershad could not participate in the [[Bangladeshi general election, 2001|2001 elections]].
Ershad appealed against the verdict in the High Court Division which affirmed the conviction, but reduced the sentence to five years on 24 August 2004. He was also fined 55 million taka.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Szfqq7ruqWgC|title=Bangladesh: Past and Present|last=Ahmed|first=Salahuddin|date=2004-01-01|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=9788176484695|page=231|language=en}}</ref> He was released with a year and half remaining on his sentence. Ershad's then wife [[Rowshan Ershad]] was fined Ten thousand taka.<ref name=":1" /> Shukur Ali Pradhan another accused in the case had filed to get the tower back from the government. The high court ruled in his favor but the supreme court overturned it and the property remains in government ownership.<ref name=":1" />
Ershad, the former [[President of Bangladesh]] and chief of the [[Jatiya Party (Ershad)|National Party]] (''Jatiya Party''), was released on [[bail]] on April 9, 2001 after serving four months in jail in [[Dhaka]].
== Legacy == The tower was repurposed as an Software park by the government of Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-168136|title = A good year for IT|date = 2010-12-30|website = The Daily Star|access-date = 2016-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-165201|title = Software park in Janata Tower next year|last = Bhuiyan|first = Mehdi Musharraf|date =|website = thedailystar.net|publisher = The Daily Star|access-date = 2016-05-06}}</ref> Matiur Rahman Chowdhury, editor of the daily [[Manab Zamin|Manab zamin]] was sentenced to jail in May 2002 for contempt of court. The paper had published a transcript of a phone conversation between Ershad and a High court judge in which Ershad was seeking a more favourable verdict in the Janata tower case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-151450|title=SC slams on contempt|date=2010-08-19|website=The Daily Star|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref>
